column168: At approximately 9:05 p.m. on August 1, 2013 it was reported that tank car TCIX 4359 was found leaking from the top appurtenances in the KCS Laredo Yard. KCS employee notified CID and appropriate notifications were made and responders activated.    After verification of securement of trackage and upon further inspection, it was determined that the leak source was 2 manway swing bolts were found in the down position and another another bolt was found less than tool tight. It was also noted that the manway gasket was misaligned. Responder successfully re-positioned manway gasket and tightened manway bolts in the appropriate pattern. The car was then released back into transportation.      * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 13-Consignee + address reported was the consignee + address reported on the waybill (Waybill# 306487). The consignee address is different from the final destination reported on the waybill. Both addresses are as follows:    Consignee + Address:  BASF MEXICANA SA DE CV  AV LICENCIADO ANGEL OTERO RIVERO 8  INDUSTRIAS TULPETLAC  ECATEPEC DE MORELOS, EM 55107    Final destination + address:  ADJUVANTS UNLIMITED INC  3633 CHARLES PAGE BLVD  PARKVIEW, OK 74127    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.     It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.  Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car GATX 59964 in the railyard was reported emanating a stenched propane like odor with a patch of frost/ice observed adhering to the outside of its protective valve housing cover. GATX 59964 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting immediate inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported finding the A-end liquid valve partially open with its closure plug not tool tight. The responder closed the A-end liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug which ending any further commodity release. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Intact shipper seal LANSING NGL SVC. 06873 was replaced by seal numbered 6881333. After additional monitoring, no further odor was detectable and the ice/frosting on the valve housing cover evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On August 4, 2013 at 1900 hours personnel in the CSXT Hopewell Yard discovered UTLX200993, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Methyl Keytone leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Sasol North America was contacted via CHEMTREC report number 2013-0804-00056.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product dripping from the threaded connection of the 2 inch plug with the bottom outlet cap.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Sasols representative Marcus Boutte at 337-494-5140.   Contractor personnel replaced the defective plug and temporarily secured the rail car.  The shipper, Sasol contacted the Federal Railroad Administration to obtain a one-time movement approval due to the fact that the bottom outlet valve may be damaged allowing product to leak past the closure.  On August 5th the FRA granted a verbal OTMA FRA-130805R2V.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause code: 551 - Valve body - other    5(5+3+0) + (2+0) = 80 NARRI

column168: Residue tank car PROX 31470 was reported venting in the railyard and it was cordoned-off awaiting inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported finding no shipper seal at the valve housing cover. The vapor valve was found partially open with its closure plug not applied. The vapor valve's closure plug along with one of the liquid valve's closure plugs were laying atop the pressure plate within the valve housing area. The responder closed the vapor valve, applied and tool tightened the unapplied closure plugs. After all the valves were secured, no further venting was detectable.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car RCRX 1100 was reported emanating a commodity odor/vapor in the railyard. RCRX 1100 was cordoned off awaiting inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder's inspection of RCRX 1100 revealed that its fill hole cover was not fully secured, as one securement eye bolt had broken with the other two bolts intact. The damaged eye bolt had fractured at the upper threaded area where the seal hole is located. Temporary repairs were made to secure the fill hole cover. No liquid commodity had leaked.  RCRX 1100 was deemed safe to move and it was isolated in the railyard. The shipper forwarded a replacement securement eye bolt and it was applied with the fill hole cover secured by 1230 hrs. CDT, 8/09/2013. No further vapor release was detectable afterwards.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: ):   Orlando Silvera (TSU driver) driving a flatbed # 4133 made a delivery at Chem Quip Pools on 8/2/13 at approx. 11:00 AM. When he completed the delivery of Chem Quip purchased goods, Orlando decided to re-stack (onto an additional pallet for each) the 2 remaining pallets, containing three (3) each Sulfuric Acid 93% 55 gallon drums, on the back of the trailer to avoid complications at the next delivery site (as driver claims the original pallets were bowing inward and prevented his pallet jack from fully entering the pallets, however, pallets were not secured from driver upon his return to the Medley facility to determine if this was indeed the case). Orlando  pushed the tips of the pallet jack in as far as they would go, lifted one end of the pallet, and drug it to the rear of the trailer. Then to restack the pallets, Orlando used a Chem Quip forklift.  The forklift was on the ground at the rear of the TSUI trailer.  He moved the forks under the original pallet and lifted the original pallet high enough to slide a fresh pallet underneath then lowered the original pallet on top.  However, when performing this operation on the second pallet, Orlando punctured one of the Sulfuric Acid 93% drums with the forklift fork, causing a 3” wide opening.  Sulfuric Acid spilled from the drum onto the trailer and then to the customer’s parking lot.  The forklift fork also squeezed/pinched another drum on the same pallet, but this drum did not leak. Orlando entered his trailer, and turned the drum on its side to stop the leak.  He proceeded to borrow a hose from the customer and wash down not only his trailer, but the affected parking lot with water. Customer assisted Orlando, adding Sodium Bicarbonate onto the spilled area.    Orlando notified called Miami Dispatch (Joe Isla) to report what had taken place directly after laying the drum on its side and washing the trailer and floor (approx. 11:10-15 AM).  Joe Isla advised Leo DeLeon, Plant Manager, of a drum of Sulfuric Acid leaking at ChemQuip, on the TSUI trailer.  Leo and Joe called to customer, asking them to move it with their forklift truck (with Leo advising them off to do safely).  After the conversation, Leo dispatched to the scene two plant employees, one an emergency responder, Jesus Carjuapoma, and Percy DeLeon, Medley drum fill operator, along with an overpack drum, extra drums, neutralization materials. Leo stated it was his understanding that the drum failed due to damage, but he was not aware the drum was struck with by our driver with a forklift truck.    When I, Jaimie Johnson, returned to the plant in the afternoon, I was notified at approximately 1:15P by Leo D’ Leon  (Plant Manager) of ChemQuip having a leaking Sulfuric Acid drum. I questioned Leo about why they would have a leaking Sulfuric Acid drum when they do not buy Sulfuric Acid, and Leo stated to me ChemQuip had received their order and that they, my assumption at the time was he meant ChemQuip, had damaged the Sulfuric drums whi
column169: A) Disciplinary action for TSUI driver for operating a forklift, causing release of chemical and failure to take photographs as well as complete a vehicle incident report  B) Disciplinary action for TSUI Supervisor, failure to drug test and failure to follow company policy for reporting, documenting incident (including ensuring the driver has taken photographs of the scene)  C) Disciplinary action for Branch Manager, failure to drug test and notified Regional Manager, Risk Management Specialist  D) Coaching for Plant Manager, reviewing of incident/accident reporting & documentation requirements  E) Retrain all Branch Management Personnel on company reporting and response to chemical releases, including dispatch of Environmental Clean-Up Company thru insurance firm as well as use of Emergency Responders for response only.  F) Safety meeting with all drivers, including bulk drivers, that they are never permitted to operate a forklift or use a forklift as a means to raise or lower themselves to deliver a load.  TSUI drivers not trained to operate, and even if they are, can not use a customer’s forklift equipment.  G) Safety meeting with all drivers, including bulk drivers, that they are not permitted to rinse a chemical spill with water

column168: It was reported that the drums of UN1719 were shrink-wrapped together on a pallet. The drums slid off the skid due to a load shift, and a nail in the pallet punctured the bottom of one of the drums. The driver turned the drum on its side after inspecting the load shift, to prevent further release of material. Approximately 2 gallons was released to the trailer floor. column169: Load was a COFC intermodal load; spill occured/occured at the receiver, sometime after deramping from the rail carrier.  At this time, there is no indication the cargo was not loaded & secured properly, nor is there indication of a hard stop by motor carrier nor of mishandling during rail transit.  Most likely the cause was mishandling during unloading.  Receiver will be informed to be more careful during unloading.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was being transferred from one trailer to another at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  While sitting on the dock for approximately 10 minutes, one of the supersacks was found to be leaking a small amount of liquid.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the sack into a suitable salvage container.  The spilled liquid was cleaned up with a suitable absorbant material which was also placed into the salvage container.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The material was a sludge which was leaking liquid.  The shipper was notified to improve their solidification process prior to further shipments.

column168: While picking up a loaded trailer inside the shipper's plant, when the driver reached the area near the gate where it is permissible to inspect the vehicle prior to leaving, a leak was noticed coming from the dome.  A response crew was summoned by the plant and found that the bleeder valve and bolts on the dome lid had not been properly tightened by the plant personnel.  The spilled material was cleaned up with absorbant pads and taken back into the plant.  The driver checked all closures and then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The plant admitted that their personnel had failed to properly secure the dome lid and promised to take appropriate action.

column168: While unloading a box truck at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a 250 gallon tote loaded with waste antifreeze was moved to the lift gate of the truck with a pallet jack so that the forklift on the dock could pick it up and load it onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  The excess weight on the lift gate caused it to fail and lower onto the ground.  The forklift blade then punctured the tote as it was moving causing approximately 25 gallons of liquid to be released onto the concrete containment area of the ground.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material, transfering it and the remaining contents of the damaged tote into another tote.  The shipment was then loaded onto the trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The spill was reported to the Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality, incident number 135614.
column169: Proper material handling procedures were reviewed with all dock personnel.

column168: While unloading a shipment of hazardous waste at the intermediate truck transfer facility at the intended disposal facility, a puddle of liquid was found on the trailer floor.  The dock personnel donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and discovered that the leak came from the edge of a removable lid on a drum.  The lid was removed and it was found that less than 1/4 of the gasket was in place.  The gasket was replaced, cleanup material placed into the drum and tightened per applicable closure instructions.  The drum was then accepted into the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and was to review proper drum closure procedures with his people.  The drum showed no signs of leaking at the time of pickup.

column168: A California PUC Hazardous Material Investigator inspecting rail cars in the railyard reported finding residue tank car CTCX 732232 emanating residue commodity vapors from its manway closure. After notification, BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected CTCX 732232 finding one of its manway securement bolt nuts not tool tight. CTCX 732232's manway gasket was inspected and found to be serviceable with no defects noted. The manway closure was then properly secured with all its securement bolt nuts properly tool tightened in the required pattern. Afterwards, no further residue commodity vapors were detectable.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On August 14, 2013 at 1600, personnel in the CSXT Barr Yard discovered UTLX 201598, Residue Alcohols, N.O.S., releasing vapors from the Vacuum Relief Valve.  The car was isolated the shipper, BioUrja Trading LLC, was contacted via CHEMTREC  report number 2013081400228.  SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a cracked O-ring in the Vacuum Relief Valve.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Kristina Autrey, 309-347-9318, with Aventine Renewable Energy.  Contractor personnel replaced the Vacuum Relief Valve.  The car will be moved under an OTMA to home shop for qualification of the new Vacuum Relief Valve.    Cause Code:  458  NARI:    2(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 28
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On August 17, 2013 at 2210, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered UTLX 25349, a loaded tank car of Toxic Liquid, Corrosive, Inorganic, N.O.S., dripping from the top of the car.  The car was isolated the shipper, Heritage-Crystal Clean was contacted via CHEMTREC  report number 2013-08-17-00137.  Summit Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to one of the manway lid securement bolts being less than tool tight and there was no manway lid gasket installed in the tank car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, Joseph Licari, at 847-783-5376.  Contractor personnel installed a nozzle gasket and secured the car for transportation.  This incident did not require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 200, 207  NARRI:  5(5+5+1) x (2+0) = 110

column168: Driver was attempting to drop loaded trailer on Martin Transport yard. Driver pulled out from under trailer, the right dolly leg began sinking into the ground tilting the trailer on it's right side. Driver was unable to get back under the trailer before it turned over on the right side. the tank struck a concrete barricade tearing a hole in the skin of the tank. Approximately 7,200 gallons of Crude Oil spilled onto the ground. Pottery Addition Volunteer Fire Department responded as well as Environmental Management Services, an environmental cleanup company. The fire department put down booms to curtail the flow of oil and Environmental Management Services cleaned up the spill. Buch's Truck Stop was closed as a precaution while the cleanup was conducted.
column169: Driver will be re-trained on policies involving dropping trailers. Martin Transport has a policy of not dropping a loaded trailer without prior approval from Management or the Safety Department. Martin company policy was not followed causing this incident to occur.

column168: CN switch crew noted a strong ammonia odor during switching operations at the Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA. All appropriate departments notified, CN's response team responded and determinted that tank car UTLX 950833(R/  TRIMETHYLAMINE, ANHYDROUS, UN1080, Class 2.1)  was the source of the odor. A closer inspection was conducted of UTLX 950833, seal # INT 157225 was noted intact and upon opening the pressure housing, a leak detection solution was used to locate the leak source.  Upon being sprayed onto the "A" end liquid valve plug, bubbles immediately started to form around the plug. The valve handle was checked and turned an additonal 1/4 turn closed.  The valve plug was checked and was noted to turn an additonal 1/2 turn closed.  Upon securing the valve completely, the bubbling stopped and the odor dissipated.  The leak was secured and car released to the shipper for movement to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car TILX 255327, load of Combustible Liquid, n.o.s. was reported leaking by yard employees, with product around the top and down the sides.  Car was isolated and contractor called to investigate.  Opon opening the manway cover, the contractor found the car had no manway gasket.  A new manway gasket was installed, the manway cover bolts tightened to the recommeded torque value in a star pattern, and the car was released back into transportation.

column168: FRA Inspector Rowan found tank car TILX 252411 with a small leak in the manway area and product on the top of the car.  Car was isolated and a contractor was called to respond.  Contractor opened the manway and found the fiber manway gasket seriously deteriorated.  It had to be scraped out in pieces.  Gasket was replaced with 18" EPDM gasket, manway bolts tighened, and the car was rleased back into transportation.

column168: Unit is an intermodal, container on flatbed load.  Spill was noted during the rail portion of the transit and reported to JBH by rail personnel; however, the spill likely originated at the shipper.  The securment appears sound; no evidence of load shift.  The spill was due to a small crack in the center of a larger dent in the steel drum.  The crack was quite small, releasing a few ounces of paint which pooled up and eventually leaked outside of the container where it was noted by rail personnel.  Most likely this dent occured during loading, likely from a blow received by other cargo handled by forklift or similar loading device.  Most likely the shipper did not notice the leak when they were still loading it as the crack was quite small.
column169: Photos and a contractor report will be shared with the shipper - this appears to be a random case of mishandling and not the result of any systematic mispractice.

column168: DRIVER WAS FILLING A TRACTOR-TRAILER-PUP COMBINATION AT THE CHEVRON LOADING RACK IN PASCO, WA. THE DRIVER REPOSITIONED THE RIG TO CONTINUE LOADING PROCESS WITHOUT DISCONNECTING THE VAPOR RECOVERY, GROUNDING CABLE, AND LOAD ARM FROM THE PUP. THE LINE FROM THE API LOADHEAD TO THE TANK WAS DAMAGED AND WAS LEAKING. A DRIVER IN THE NEXT BAY SAW WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND SHUT THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER WITHIN 30 SECONDS OF THIS HAPPENING. AS THE RESULT OF THE QUICK ACTION OF THE OTHER DRIVER WE LOST 161 GALS OF GASOLINE INTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT FIELD OF THE LOADING TERMINAL.
column169: A FORMAL INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED AND PENDING THE APPROVAL FROM HR DISCIPLINE OF THE DRIVER WILL OCCUR. DURING THE INVESTIGATION A MANAGEMENT OF CHANGE ISSUE WAS IDENTIFIED ALONG WITH A POSSIBLE TRAINING GAP. WE ARE UPDATING OUR TRAINING TO INSTRUCT THE DRIVER TO ALWAYS WALK AROUND THE BACKSIDE OF THE TRAILER. THIS WILL CAUSE THE DRIVER TO WALK PAST ALL THE LOADHEADS ON THE TRAILER. THE MANAGEMENT OF CHANGE ISSUE WILL BE ADDRESSED WITH DISPATCH AND WILL BE INCLUDED AS PART OF OPERATIONS MEETING AT THE TERMINALS.

column168: Our CTMV was is storage incidental to movement at our Chesapeake Terminal. During a routine yard check, a release of product was observed on the gravel yard (parking area.) Terminal personnel transloaded the lading to another CTMV and called in an environmental contractor to remediate impacted yard.  The CTMV was cleaned and inspected.  The internal (emergency) valve mounting gasket (the gasket between the valve body and the CTMV sump) was diagnosed as defective.  The gasket was replaced, and the CTMV was then returned to service.      Our event 38214.

column168: After arrival on a BNSF intermodal train, intermodal trailer FXFZ 974538 was reported leaking an unknown liquid substance. FXFZ 974538 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area for further inspection. Contract responders inspecting the lading within FXFZ 974538 reported finding one 300 gallon poly IBC with a small cut in its lower sidewall that was caused by a protruding piece of metal that had fallen and wedged itself into an adjacent wooden pallet being used to fill a void space. The small cut/gash (estimated at 1 cm in length) was plugged to stop this slow leak. The remaining commodity in this compromised IBC was transloaded into a 250 gallon poly IBC and a 55 gallon poly drum. Both of these packages were returned to the lading after all observed spillage was neutralized and cleaned.
column169: No additional comments.

column169: At 4pm August 27, 2013 PROX 41477 was reported to have material dripping from top on tank car and down the R - side of car. Emergency Response group inspected top dome area of car and found material coming from the valve protective housing cover. After opening of housing cover noted a hissing noise and some drop of material coming from bottom flange area of unloading connection valve. The vacuum relief valve located on top of manway cover was pushed down to release the pressure in the car. After this was done the material stopped dipping from the bottom flange area of the valve. Further inspection of the area in question found the 4 mounting bolt nuts were loose by hand. The nuts in question were made tool tight and car was released for service.It should be noted the temp. at the time was 100 degrees (F) which probably increased the pressure in the vessel and creating the leak to become noticeable.    Better inspection at loading facility to insure all closures are closed and tool tight and that all securement bolts, nuts etc. are in proper order and tool tight.
column198: terminal Railroad Association of St. Louis

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 202128 was reported leaking commodity from its pressure relief device (PRD) while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 202128 finding the B-end 75 psi pressure relief valve (PRV) had discharged commodity that was evaporating on UTLX 202128's side shell. UTLX 202128 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. A contract responder confirmed that the B-end PRV sustained a broken stem with the PRV spring and associated hardware falling inside the tank. The responder clamped-down the B-end PRV to eliminate any further commodity release from this PRV. The A-end PRV was also inspected with no defects noted. FRA OTMA (FRA-13080539) was received to transport UTLX 202128 to the nearby consignee for unloading and then to a qualified repair facility.

column168: During transportation of 275 gallons of Hydrochloric Acid, the IBC tank spontaneously burst along a formed vertical seam in the plastic. The rupture was approximately 28 inches long and about 200 gallons of Acid drained from the tank. The driver of the truck drove about 4 blocks before realizing there was an issue. After realizing there was a spill he immediately pulled over and with the assistance of a police officer cleared the area and called for emergency response. After the scene was secured by police and fire responders, the fire responders and a Horizon employee were able to open the back of the truck, determine the cause of the leak and the remaining acid.
column169: All testing of the tank was within compliance. To help prevent the possibility of future tank failure we have implemented further training on looking for tank testing compliance and tank condition. Sense the tank that failed was owned and maintained by another company we implemented a policy that we will inspect all tanks as they are delivered to our facility and will not accept tanks that are more than 10 years old. The tank that failed was in full compliance, but was 15 years old.

Contract responders inspecting for the leak source within JBHU 252390 reported finding one palletized 55 gallon steel drum with a dented sidewall near this drum's bottom rolling hoop. A small crack was noted in the rolling hoop at the dented location where some commodity had seeped out. The crack was sealed and the drum was placed into an over-pack drum. column168: On August 2, 2013, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container TCNU976426 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950 AEROSOLS flammable). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column25: RPMG LLC by KAAPA Ethanol LLC
column168: Entrained tank car TILX 196205 staged for delivery to the consignee was reported dripping commodity from it bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected TILX 196205 and reported commodity drips from the BOV's mounting flange connection. The responder tool tightened the BOV's four mounting flange bolt nuts to end the slow commodity drip. The drippage to the ground area under the BOV (mostly on a rail crosstie) evaporated. Response was concluded when TILX 196205 was released to proceed to its destination at 2055 hrs. PDT 8/24/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column25: Taylor Chemical Ltd by SERVCO Chemical
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Tank car UTLX 631192 in the railyard was reported dripping residue commodity from its top fitting area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected UTLX 631192. The responders reported no shipper seal at the valve housing cover and commodity drips were emanating from the liquid valve's closure plug. The responders reduced the internal pressure within UTLX 631192 via the vapor valve which took almost an hour. Afterwards, the commodity drips from the liquid valve's closure plug ceased. The liquid valve's operating handle was on the valve stem but was not secured by a retaining nut; the liquid valve's closure plug was not tool tight. It appeared that the valve housing cover when closed contacted the liquid valve's operating handle forcing it downwards past the valve stop which opened the liquid valve; when coupled with a loose closure plug and internal tank car pressure allowed commodity to escape via the loose closure plug. Responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened its closure plug to secure this fitting. The liquid valve's operating handle was removed from its valve stem and placed within the valve housing area. Spillage on UTLX 631192's side shell was neutralized and cleaned. A small amount of ground spillage was also neutralized. Response was concluded by 1015 hrs. CDT, 8/28/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was being offloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  The forklift operator dropped a flex bin onto the dock floor while turning, causing the seam on the corner edge of the box to split along with the inner plastic bag.  Approximately 10 lbs of the material spilled onto the floor.  The operator donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and repacked the spilled material into a new flex bin.  The shipment was then loaded onto the trailer without further incident.  The incident was reported to Ohio EPA incident number 1308-31-1965
column169: The forklift operator was cautioned to slow down when operating the forklift.

column168: A truck containing various shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  Upon opening the door, a drum was found to be tipped over and leaking from the bung, which was popped out.  The driver donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage drum, along with the absorbant material used to contain the spill.  No liquid left the truck floor.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The spill was reported to the LA state police, incident number 18281.

column168: At about 2330 hours on August 22, 2013 John Vergis, Assistant Environmental Officer, was called about a possible leaking LPG car in the Wheeling and Lake Erie Rail Yard in Brewster, Ohio.  Once on scene, it was told by the crew that when switching, they could smell a strong odor of gas coming from this car every time it passed them.  They were instructed to set the car aside and take the engine out of the area.  Once John Vergis was on scene, it was noticed after investigation that the vapor valve on the car was night tight and the valve plug was less than hand tight.  After tightening the valve handle and also the plug, the leak was stopped and the car re sealed and sent on its way.
column169: A better checklist for the securement of tank cars before shipment needs to be adopted by the shipper.

column168: On 08/20/2013, at 1945, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard in Waycross GA discovered FPAX 972010, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid N.O.S., Ethylene Glycol, leaking from the bottom outlet valve cap. The car was isolated and the shipper Nan Ya Plastics, local, state, GA DNR and the NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2013-0820-00347. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve handle in the open position. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Charles Bethany 361-987-7465. Contractor personnel closed the bottom outlet valve handle and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code:148  NARRI:5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: Shipment was not offloaded from truck. Odor noticed prior to offload from truck.  Shipment insepcted and it was found that the odor was caused by the inner liner not being closed/ sealed correctly. The inner was a thin plastic bag and it was inteneed to be sealed with a zip tie type closure. The zip tie was not closed al the way and the haz mat contents were able to spill out of the inner bag and into the fiberboard outer carton, this caused a stong odor, and a small amount of the haz mat also came out of the 4 of the fiberboard boxes and spilled onto the truck bed/skids.The freight forwarder was advised of this situation. This shipment was not accepted into the airlines warehouse and not offloaded from the truck.  The freight forwarder manager was advised of the shipment would be returned and to take appropriate action.The FAA was advised, the agent was Mary Ann Gera Maryann.H.Gera@faa.gov . The freight forwarder BDP was advised by Lufthansa that the incomplete closure of the inner liner , and possible the weakness of the inner linner appeared to be the casue of the odor and leakage. column25: High Sierra Crude Oil Marketing LLC by Colorado Sweet Gold LLC
column168: Tank car TAEX 2402 was reported leaking commodity from its manway closure during movement in the railyard. TAEX 2402 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection from contract responders. Responder's reported the manway gasket was misaligned and misshaped. All other valves and fittings were found secure. A new 20 inch Nitrile manway gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly secured.  Non-evaporated spillage was wiped and no ground impact from spillage was observed. Response was concluded by 1500 hrs. MDT, 8/30/2013.   Intact shipper seals High Sierra Trans 09150 and 09128 at the protective hosing cover and the manway were replaced by seals TIS 5199 and TIS 5200 respectively.  TAEX 2402's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 8-10-2013 at approximately 04:52 A.M. the train crew on the MAVBT 09 smelled a strong odor emitting from tank car OLNX 114016.  Thomas Robinson Manager of Hazardous Materials was called to respond.  Manager Robinson determined the leak  to be coming from the securement bolts of the pressure relief device. The A-end, right side bolt appeared to be loose.  The crows foot wrench from the Chlorine C Kit was utilized and the bolt was tightened securing the leak. All of the bolts on all of the valves were checked for security and no additional bolts were found loose.  The protective housing was then washed out with water and a secondary assessment on all of the valves and plugs was performed. A chlorine specific colorimetric tube was used to check air quality in the protective housing and to verify that the tank was secure.
column169: Mr. Bruce Fleming from Olin Corporation called Kevin Blackwell from the FRA to determine if a movement approval was needed for this car to continue to destination.  Mr. Blackwell determined that no movement approval was required according to the Code of Federal Regulations.

column168: On 8-15-2013 at 08:27 A.M. an odor was reported at the Livonia train yard in Livonia, LA by yard employees.  Manager of Hazardous Materials Thomas Robinson was called to respond and investigate.  Manager Robinson discovered tank car CCBX 2409 releasing from a broken thermometer well.  The tank car was isolated and a plug was placed on the broken thermometer well.  The car was pressure tested with no leaks discovered.  An OTMA-3 was requested to the FRA by the shipper.  The car was released from hold status by Manager Robinson on 8-17-2013 and routed back to Taft, LA for unloading.

SJ Transportation Co., Inc. (SJ) driver entered GlobalFoundries Malta, NY plant to load tank trailer LTV253 with Waste Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, Inorganic NOS (Copper Sulfate, Sulfuric Acid), 8, PG II.  Upon completion of loading process the plant side operator shut off their pump and closed off their line.  SJ driver started his pump to clear SJ’s hoses, once that was completed he closed the internal valve, wiped the inside of the external valve dry and then closed and capped the external valve.  He removed the fittings, dried them with a hazmat pad over a 5 gallon bucket and stored the hoses in LTV253’s hose tray.  He then released vacuum on the trailer, put on some additional PPE went on LTV253 to get a stick reading of the tank for the customer.  When he went to the back of the trailer to sign the manifest there was a small drip going into the 5 gallon bucket that had a hazmat pad in it.  SJ driver uncapped the external valve; some additional material went into the 5 gallon bucket.  He checked the external valve handle, he tightened the handle and the leaking stopped.  GlobalFoundries requested SJ driver not wipe the external valve dry and leave the external valve uncapped for approximately 10 minutes to ensure there was no more leaking.  SJ driver then put vacuum back on the trailer, there was no more leaking and GlobalFoundries personnel was satisfied that the trailer was no longer leaking and released LTV253 to leave the plant.  No material ever hit the ground; all material was caught and contained in a 5 gallon bucket that had a hazmat absorbent pad in it.  SJ driver estimates about ¼ of a gallon of material was released into the 5 gallon bucket.
column169: Upon SJ driver’s return to the yard he was retrained in vacuum procedures and trailer # LTV253 was taken out of service and scheduled for inspection in our maintenance facility.  It was discovered that the external valve handle was cracked which prevented the valve from closing properly when the driver originally closed the external valve.  The handle on the external valve was replaced and the trailer was put back in service.

column168: Employee was pulling the Anhydrous Ammonia nurse tank out to the Sellards Farm.  As he was traveling down a hill Eastbound at 15 mph on Windy Rd in Ford County the trailer started to fish tail.  The trailer hit the berm on the dirt road and started to turn over, because of the tank turning over it snapped the hitch on the pickup.  The safety chains kept the pickup with the tank.  The Trailer ended up on its side the roll cage around the valves was damaged and the liquid valve was sheared off allowing a slow release of anhydrous ammonia.  The wind was out of the south at 10 mph on a sunny day. The employee was able to pull the pickup away from the tank and have someone bring out a water tank and started to pump water on the tank to slow the leaking.  An empty anhydrous ammonia trailer was positioned along side the leaking nurse tank.  A hose was connected between the two tanks to liquid transfer as much anhydrous as possible.  After the transfer the pressure in the leaking tank had dropped to the point where no more vapors were leaking.  A wrangler was used to lift the damaged nurse tank onto its wheels on the road. The damaged tank was transported back to the anhydrous ammonia plant empty.
column169: Provide employees with additional driving safety tips when towing tanks.  Advise employees of the driving dangers traveling downhill while towing equipment on sanded roads.  Further advise of the driving dangers when encountering sand ridges on road.  The tank was sent off to replace the valves and roll cage along with an inspection of the tank by a certified inspector is being completed.

column168: On August 23, 2013, a 55 gallon fiber drum containing what was thought to be UN1500, later to be discovered as UN1479 Oxidizing Solid got wet from water leaking into a trailer. The water compromised the fiber drum allowing for moisture to get into the drum and react with the powder material. This reaction caused an over pressurization of the drum resulting in a blow out and releasing the entire contents of the drum onto the concrete dock. No waterways or drains were impacted by the material. An environmental contractor responded and collected the material containerizing it into poly over pack drums while keeping the material cool under fans to dry out the moisture. The impacted area of dock was washed/ wiped down. The material was that was over packed was dried out over several days and then sealed to be sent back to the shipper.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: Residue tank car PROX 98661 was reported venting in the railyard and it was cordoned-off. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected PROX 98661. Responders reported an audible vapor hiss emanating from within the valve housing cover which was not properly pinned closed and without a shipper seal. Responders found both liquid valves not fully closed along with the vapor valve partially open. Also, all these valve's closure plugs were not tool tight. The responders closed the valves and tool tightened the closure plugs which ended any further vapor release. The valve housing cover was closed and pinned correctly with seal BNSF 03954419 applied. Response was concluded by 0545 hrs. CDT, 8/31/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED FROM BACK OF TRAILER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF TO ROAD SHOULDER, PENDING INVESTIGATION. EP&S OF VT OF SCRANTON, PA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, FREE PRODUCT WAS DETECTED WITHIN ROADSIDE SOILS. EP&S OF VT INSPECTED THE TRAILER, AND DISCOVERED ONE (1) 300-GALLON TOTE HAD BEEN DAMAGED IN TRANSIT, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 115 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT. EP&S OF VT PROCEEDED TO PLUG TANK AND RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUID FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR. EP&S OF VT ALS EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOILS ALONG THE ROAD SHOULDER, WHICH WERE CONTAINERIZED INTO A ROLLOFF BOX, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. POST CONFIRMATION SAMPLES WERE PULLED FROM EXCAVATION PIT, AND SITE WAS RESTORED TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. THERE WAS NO IMPACT OR THREAT TO STATE WATERS AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: On 08/29/2013 at approximately 12:00pm, a company driver had justed loaded the Moore 1-1H Lease and was in-route to the Wynnewood Station.  While traveling westbound on Pleasant Rd at a speed of approximately 25 mph, the driver approached a blind hill and maneuvered the truck to the right shoulder.  Upon descending the hill, the driver noticed a vehicle approaching from the East.  The driver then maneuvered the truck further to the right and onto the edge of a newly applied "chip seal" road.  The driver's estimated speed at this point was approximately 20 mph.  As soon as the right steer tire on the truck reached the edge of the "chip seal" road, it drifted off the road and down into a steep ravine approximately 3 ft. deep.  Once the steer tire reached the bottom of the ravine, the load shifted and caused the driver to lose control of the truck.  The truck and trailer overturned on its passenger side and then rotated over to its driver's side before coming to rest.  The driver was not seriously injured, and no product was released from the cargo tank.  Emergency Services responded to the scene along with Company personnel.  The truck's load was transferred to another truck and wrecker services uprighted the truck successfully with no loss of product.
column169: The root cause of this lay-over accident was due to inattentive driving.  Contributing factor included a newly "chip seal" road surface consisting of an 8-12" soft edge which deceived the driver in believing the road edge was solid and sufficiently improved.      Additional awareness training on the factors that caused and contributed to this event is warranted.  Company drivers shall participate in an accident review process to include discussion on the hazards of inattentive driving and risk factors or roads with no improved shoulder.

column168: AFTER UNLOADING THE TANKER OF CAUSTIC SODA INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK, THE DRIVER CLOSED BOTH THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES ON THE TANKER AND OPENED THE AIR VALVE TO THE DISCHARGE VALVE TO BLOW OUT THE TRANSFER HOSE INTO THE CUSTOMER'S SYSTEM. AFTER ALLOWING THE AIR TO RUN FOR A WHILE, HE CLOSED THE CUSTOMER'S VALVE IN THE PIPING AT THE HOOKUP POINT AND THEN DISCONNECTED THE HOSE FROM THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TANKER. HE THEN LAID THE TANKER END OF THE HOSE ON THE GROUND AND WENT TO DISCONNECT THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMER'S HOOKUP POINT AND APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF CAUSTIC SODA DRIBBLED OUT OF THE HOSE AND ONTO THE GROUND.
column169: THE SOLUTION TO PREVENTING A RECURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT IS THAT THE TANKER HOSE WILL BE DRAINED INTO THE 5 GALLON PAIL THEY HAVE WITH THEM WHEN MAKING TANKER DELIVERIES. ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THEY FOLLOW THESE PROCEDURES.

column168: on 12Aug2013 World Courier submitted a package for shipping. After checking They are in compliance with TSA approved security, package was accepted for shipment to ORD. As no dangerous goods declared package was sent through regular TSA screening. At 09:45 I received a call that the package had been opened by TSA and it was a dangerous good. 4 TSA employees experienced adverse affects from opening package. One experienced a burning sensation on his face and the other two reported throat and nose irritation. The fourth who carried the box experienced welts on his forearms and was sent to the hospital for observation. I located MSDS sheets inside box that stated it was a dangerous good. I resealed the box and brought it back to AA office. At this time I experienced numbness in my left pinkie finger. TSA notified Reno Fire/Police. I was placed under observation until 1600 at which time I was allowed to leave.

column168: Tank car SRIX 30063 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area while in the railyard. Immediate inspection by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed that the sample line valve's pipe nipple had cracked and broken off above the pressure plate which allowed commodity to escape from this open orifice. Responders temporarily plugged the sample line's open orifice ending the commodity release by 1429 hrs. CDT 8/30/2013. Responders procured replacement pipe nipple fittings and reassembled the sample line valve. The repaired sample line valve was installed and secured into the pressure plate by 1540 hrs. CDT 8/30/2013. Spillage on the side shell of SRIX 30063 evaporated along with a small area of ground impact under SRIX 30063  Later, SRIX 30063's vacuum relief valve (VRV) was observed venting. The stuck open VRV was removed by contract responders and its orifice plugged with a pipe plug.  SRIX 30063's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was in the year 2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and the mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column17: Reclaimed Energy Div. Superior Oil Co., Inc.
column168: A shipment of 3M was received on 08/26/2013.  Upon receipt, it was noticed that a drum was leaking in the trailer.  The material was contained and cleaned up.

Tank car UTLX 57786 in the railyard was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area. Initial inspection of UTLX 57786 by contract responders resulted in a suspected leak source at the top fitting pressure plate's flange connection. All the securement bolts and nuts were tested for tool tightness. Afterwards, a small leak was observed during a movement examination and UTLX 57786 was isolated in the railyard awaiting transloading into another suitable tank car.    On 8/30/2013, other contract responders preparing to transload UTLX 57786, pressured-up UTLX 57786 and observed an active commodity leak at the less than tool tight 3 inch liquid valve's threaded connection. The liquid valve was removed, new Teflon sealant applied to all threaded areas, reinserted and tool tightened. Afterwards, internal pressure was increased and no further leakage was observed at the liquid valve's threaded connection; and no indication of any leakage at the pressure plate's flange connection was evident. Commodity within UTLX 57786 was transferred into another suitable tank car by 1610 hrs. MDT 8/30/2013 without further incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: ON 8/12/2013 CENTRL RECEIVING (CR) AT CSU RECEIVED A DAMAGED RETURNED PACKAGE FROM UPS GROUND. THE BOX HAD NO DOT SHIPPING PAPERWORK OR LABELING. CR NOTIFIED THE SHIPPERS IN THE GRIFFORD BUILDING ON THE CSU CAMPUS THAT THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN RETURNED AND WAS AVAILABLE FOR THEM TO PICK UP AT CR. THE GIFFORD LABORATORY PERSONNEL WENT TO CR AND TOOK POSSESSION OF THE BOX AND PROCEEDED TO REPACKAGE THE BOX INTO TWO SEPARATE BOXES IN THE CR PARKING LOT IN ORDER TO SHIP IT BACK TO PENN STATE. MR. KELSO, A DOT TRAINED INDIVIDUAL FROM CR, OBSERVED THE REPACKING AND OBSERVED NUMEROUS CHEMICALS WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGE. MR. KELSO STATED TO THE OCCUPANTS THAT THE PACKAGE COULD NOT BE SHIPPED IN THIS MANNER AND THAT PROPER PACKAGING, PAPERWORK AND LABELING WERE REQUIRED. THE LAB PERSONNEL TOOK THE ORIGINAL PACKAGE AND THE TWO BOXES OF CHEMICALS WITH THEM AND TRANSPORTED THE BOXES TO THE GIFFORD BUILDING TO REPACK THE CONTENTS. MR. KELSO CALLED MR. GIGLIA FROM ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES (EHS), CHEMICAL MANAGEMENT UNIT TO REPORT THE RETURNED BOX CONTAINING CHEMICALS. MR. GIGLIA THEN WENT TO CR LATER THAT MORNING AND PICKED UP THE SHIPPING PAPERWORK.  ON THE MORNING OF 8/13/2013 MR. GIGLIA WENT TO GIFFORD AND TALKED TO OFFICE PERSONNEL TO GET IN CONTACT WITH THE DEPARTMENT HEAD, DR. PAGLIASSOTI. THE DEPARTMENT HEAD WAS OUT OF TOWN, BUT THE OFFICE PERSONNEL SENT DR. PAGLIASSOTTI AN E-MAIL TO CONTACT MR. GIGLIO. MR. GIGLIO WENT BACK TO THE LABE THAT AFTERNOON AND PICKED UP THE ORIGINAL PACKAGE AND THE TWO (2) BOXES OF CHEMICALS. AT THIS TIME, MR. GIGILO SPOIKE WITH SEVERAL LAB PERSONNEL PRESENT AND ALSO WITH AN INDIVIDUAL ON THE PHONE IN THE PI'S LABORATORY AT PENN STATE. MR. GIGLIO INFORMED EVERYONE THAT HE WOULD BE TAKING POSSESSION OF ALL MATERIALS. THE BOXES WERE SEALED AND ALL MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO CSU'S HAZARDOUS WASTE FACILITY.  ON 8/14/2013 MR. GIGLIO HAD A LENGTHY PHONE CONVERSATION WITH THE PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR (PI). THE PI INDICATED NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR LIQUIDS WERE IN THE PACKAGE. MR. GIGLIO ALSO RECEIVED AN EMAIL FROM THE PI LATER IN THE DAY STATING THAT MR. GIGLIO EXPLAINED THE SITUATION AND THAT THE CHEMICALS WOULD LIKELY NOT BE SHIPPED AND HE SHOULD PURCHASE NEW CHEMICALS AND THAT MR. GIGLIO WOULD REPORT TO DR. PAGLIASSOLTTI ON ANY UPDATES. ON 8/15/2013 MR. GIGLIO WENT THROUGH THE BOXES TO IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS. MR. GIGLIO NOTED THAT THE ORIGINAL BOX HAD BEEN PLACED IN A PLASTIC LINER AND THE BOX AND LINER PLACED INSIDE ANOTHER CARDBOARD BOX FOR RETURN SHIPMENT. HE ALSO NOTICED THAT HERE WAS A MIXTURE OF SOLID AND LIQUID CHEMICALS INSIDE THE BOX AND THAT THREE OF THE BOTTLE OF CHEMICALS HAD BROKEN IN SHIPMENT, NONE OF WHICH WERE DOT REGULATED. HE REPORTED HIS FINDS TO MR. GRAHAM, MR. PAGLIASSOTTI, AND MR. KELSO. THE CHEMICALS WERE CLASSIFIED AND TOTAL AMOUNTS CALCULATED. THE BOXES CONTAINED 124 CHEMICALS, 9 OF WHICH WERE DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. ON 8/16/2013 MR. GIGLIO AND MR. PAGLIASSOTTI EXCHANGED E-MAILS REQUESTING SPEC
column169: The web page for the Department of Central Receiving, under "Shipping and Receiving" states that "Dangerous Good Shipping (Hazardous Materials) - All Dangerous Goods being shipped must have a declaration that is completed in person at the Shipping Desk. Click the button for more information.  Pressing the button provides the following information:  Dangerous Goods  Effective January 10th, 2011, all Dangerous Goods under the Department of Transportation (DOT) regulations are now REQUIRED to be physically brought to the Shipping Desk here at Central Receiving by the Shipper.  When you arrive with the package you will be required to complete all Dangerous Goods documentation electronically while at the Shipping Desk. You may pre-fill the forms below ONLY AS A REFERENCE, as all the information must be entered into the Carrier's (FedEx/UPS) specific software application and must be completed by you on our computers here. The forms must then be signed to be processed.  DISCLAIMER  Proper training is required under federal and/or state regulations to handle dangerous goods and/or hazardous material. All persons and entities must comply with all federal regulations, including but not limited to the specific training requirements of 49 C.F.R. (172.704)  Central Receiving provides these materials as a service, to be used as guidelines to assist properly trained shippers. The materials provided by Central Receiving in no way alter, satisfy, or influence any federal or state requirements. The attached information provided does not meet training requirements as required by DOT49 CFR.  The study and/or use of these materials does not qualify an individual to prepare, package, transport, or otherwise handle dangerous goods or hazardous material.  The information contained in this document is subject to update due to changing government regulations. The use of this document assumes responsibility for complying with all applicable laws and regulations regarding the shipment of Dangerous Goods.

column168: Our truck was hit head on by another truck and it burst in to flames. The amount of product that actually released is a best guess estimate because the cargo tank burned from the top down. The cargo tank was fully intact as it burned from a puncture high on the tank according to witnesses. It took approximately 2 hours for the truck to melt down from the fire as it consumed the gasoline that was in the cargo tank.
column169: This accident was caused by a distracted driver who made the wrong choice as to what direction to turn his vehicle when he was about to rear end another vehicle. Our driver had no chance to react according to witnesses. The driver of the vehicle that hit us was arrested three days later for Involuntary Vehicular Manslaughter. Our driver’s death resulted from poor judgment of others and not how the trucking industry delivers hazardous materials.

column168: The driver reported that about 5 gallons of product leaked from the dome of compartment 2 of the cargo tank when he backed over some bumps at the consignee. Driver was not allowed on top of the cargo tank at that plant but the plant operator stated that the dome lid was not completely secured.  Product got on the outside of the cargo tank and areas of the pavement.  We called out an emergency response vendor to clean off the cargo tank and the impacted areas of the pavement.
column169: The driver received performance enhancement training to stress the importance of a proper pretrip and postrip inspection.  He failed to make sure the dome was completely secure.

column168: Driver was transferring 700 gallons of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank in a building.  The storage tank was 900 gallon capacity and there was an understanding that there was sufficient space to hold the product.  About 15 minutes into the transfer the lid came off the storage tank and about 150 gallons spilled out before the driver could shut down.  Most of it went into a containment area with about 50 gallons going on the concrete floor.  the exact cause of the incident is not known. The driver may have used too much air pressure or the tank may have had more produt in it than originally thought.   We hired an emergency response company to handle the cleanup.
column169: The driver will receive performance enhancement training for unloading small quantities.  the customer site gauge will be checked for accuracy.

column168: A DRIVER OPERATING A VAN TRUCK WITH 6 HYPOCHLORITE IBCS WAS DRIVING NORTH ON I-295 NEAR HOPEWELL WHEN HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID SPRAYING FROM THE SIDE DOOR. HE STOPPED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE HWY AND FOUND A SMALL BUT SIGNIFICANT LEAK IN AN IBC OF HYPOCHLORITE BLEACH. THE FIRE DEPT AND A PRIVATE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND LIMITED THE RELEASE TO 100 GAL. CONTAINED BESIDE THE SHOULDER WHICH WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RECOVERED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE. THE TRUCK WAS DECONTAMINED AND FURTHER WASHED AT A CONTROLLED SITE. THE IBC WAS EXAMINED AND FOUND TO HAVE A ONE FOOT CRACK ON THE BOTTOM NEAR THE VALVE CONNECTION. PRODUCT LEAKED FOR SEVERAL HOURS UNTIL THE REMAINDER WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER IBC.
column169: WE ARE REVIEWING THE PRACTIES REGARDING THE USEFUL LIFE OF IBCS WITH OUR PRODUCTS AND ARE DRAWING UP GUIDELINES TO LIMIT THE USE OF PLASTIC 100KPS TEST IBCS TO 10-12 YEARS REGARDLESS OF TEST RESULTS. A MORE EXTENSIVE PRE-FILL INSPECTION (INCLUDING REMOVAL OF THE BOTTOM OF THE IBC FOR OLDER UNITS) HAS BEEN PROPOSED.

column168: Paul Jones, the 047 UE, was loading a decking table into his trailer. The table got wedged in the trailer and Mr. Jones tried to hit it loose with his forklift blades. One of our dock employees rushed him to the Emergency Room, Rahway Hospital, where he was given several breathing treatments but later released.

column168: DTI driver arrived and hooked up as normal. Near the end of the delivery the hose failed adjacent to the customer connection. The product sprayed upward onto the piping above, the delivery trailer and a small office directly next to the connection. Plant personnel responded and told the driver who was in the cab of his tractor, which is not allowed while actively off-loading, to hit the emergency cut off. They said the driver told them he didn't have one. driver turned off tractor to stop air into trailer and an operator closed the external valve and activated the Emergency Shut-Off. Plant personnel estimate 150 gallons was released. Soda ash was immediately applied to neutralize the acid. This plant manufactures this product directly adjacent to this acid unloading area. That product was used for neutralization.
column169: DTI Driver was given a 5 day unpaid suspension, a written warning letter to his personnel file, and remanded to refresher training to review the company's standard operating procedures before being allowed to return to work.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: UTLX 205715 was found by Chip Heard, Manager of Hazardous Materials for UPRR during routine car inspections.  Product was visible partially down the side of the car.  Upon inspection it was determined that the vacuum relief valve was being held open by the liquid valve stem and handle.  The handle was removed and the vavle adjusted to release the vacuum relief cover.  The vacuum relief reset and was activated to ensure proper operation.  The car was wiped clean and released back into transportation.

column168: On 8-28-2013 at 20:22 hours the loaded tank car OXAX 23234 was reported leaking at Viola Yard in Corpus Christi, Texas by yard employees. column168: Two loads delivered by DTI Driver same day. Second load overfilled consignee's tank. Driver did not report the spill. Consignee signature on delivery receipt is not theirs. column169: Driver retrained. Overfill alarms and strobes should be installed to warn driver. Large signage needs installed to advise of the maximum fill point allowing for 10% of tank volume for expansion. Operator should stay with drivers during unloading to have two sets of eyes to identify problems. Tanks have different readings on sets of gauges at driver loading station when compared to those behind the tanks. Tank gauge calibration recommended.

An odor of crude oil was reported to RMCC and I responded to Roseville CA on the PPRX660085 tank car.  I inspected the tank car and located the manway venting. I checked the swing bolts on the manway and all the bolts were tool tight and I was still getting an odor/gas release.  I opened the manway lid and located and misaligned gasket.  I removed the gasket and then placed it back on the car properly, then closed the manway lid and properly secured the manway lid, tightening the swing bolts to tool tight.  The car was then released for movement.  The shipper Phillips 66 was properly notified and assisted with the repair appropriately.

column168: ON AUGUST 7, 2013, CHEMICAL DELIVERY COMPANY DTI ASSOCIATES/BULK TRANSPORTATION DELIVERED TWO LOADS OF 3,200 GALLONS OF 93% SULFURIC ACID TO WEST BASIN'S EDWARD C. LITTLE WATER RECYCLING FACILITY. DURING THE SECOND DELIVERY THAT DAY BY THE SAME DRIVER MAXIMUM FILL HEIGHT AND FILLED TO APPROXIMATELY 13' WHICH CAUSED THE TANK TO OVERFILL AND SPILL OUT INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AS WELL AS SPLASH/SPRAY ONTO THE GROUND OUTSIDE OF CONTAINMENT. IN TOTAL APPROXIMATELY 120 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID SPILLED WITH APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OUTSIDE OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AND APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS INSIDE OF SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  THE DRIVER LEFT THE FACILITY AND DID NOT REPORT ANY INCIDENT TO THE ON-SITE OPERATOR UNITED WATER. WHEN THE SPILL CAME TO THE ATTENTION OF UNITED WATER ON AUGUST 7, 2013 THE AREA WAS BARRICADED WITH CAUTION TAPE TO PREVENT INJURY AND THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO REGULATORY AGENCIES INCLUDING: NRC, CAL EMA AND LOCAL CUPA AGENCY.  THE FOLLOWING DAY ON AUGUST 8, 2013 A SIT MEETING WAS HELD WITH DTI ASSOCIATES/BULK TRANSPORTATION AND THEY ARRANGED FOR A CONTRACTOR-NRC TO COME TO THE SITE TO COMMENCE THE CLEAN UP, REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND SPILLED SULFURIC ACID AS WELL AS NEUTRALIZE THE CONTAINMENT AREA. NRC CONTINUED THE CLEAN UP ON AUGUST 9 AND COMPLETED ALL THEIR WORK ON AUGUST 1OTH.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE FLORIDA TRAFFIC CRASH REPORT, THE TRANSPORT TRAILER WAS WEST BOUND ON VINE STREET AT HOAGLAND BLVD. IN THE LEFT TURN LANE. THE TRUCK PROCEEDED TO MAKE A LEFT TURN ONTO HOGLAND BLVD. ACCORDING TO OFFICER ANTHONY, WHO WITNESSED THE CRASH, THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 15 MPH, AND HALFWAY INTO THE TURN, THE TRUCK'S LEFT REAR END STARTED TO LIFT UPWARD OFF THE GROUND. THE TRUCK CONTINUED INTO ITS TURN AND CONTINUED TO ROLLOVER ONTO ITS PASSENGER SIDE, JUST SOUTH OF VINE STREET ON HOAGLAND. ACCORDING TO THE FLORIDA TRAFFIC CRASH REPORT, OFFICER ANTHONY WAS SITTING AT THE INTERSECTION AND THAT HE WITNESSED THE TRUCKING MAKING A SLOW LEFT TURN AND NO IMPROPER ACTIONS MADE BY THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER WAS NOT CITED FOR THE ACCIDENT.  ACCORDING TO CITY OF KISSIMMEE FIRE DEPARTMENT INCIDENT REPORT, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT (FD) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE INTERSECTION OF HOAGLAND BLVD. AND VINE STREET IN RESPONSE TO AN OVERTURNED TRACTOR TRAILER AT 11:09 AM. THE FD VISUALLY INSPECTED THE TRUCK AND DISCOVERED THAT THE TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED AND LEAKING FUEL INTO AN ADJACENT STORM SEWER CATCH BASIN. TRAILER COMPARTMENTS #1, 2 & 4 CONTAINING DIESEL FUEL WERE PUNCTURED. THE 3RD COMPARTMENT, WHICH CONTAINED GASOLINE, WAS NOT DAMAGED DURING THE ACCIDENT AND THE GASOLINE WAS RECOVERED FROM THE DAMAGED TRAILER. THE FD ESTABLISHED COMMAND AND REQUESTED CITY OF KISSIMMEE STORM AND WATER DEPARTMENT TO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. JEFF MATTERN, CITY OF KISSIMMEE STORM AND WATER SUPERINTENDENT, DETERMINED THE FLOW PATH AND DISCHARGE POINT OF THE STORM SEWER DRAIN PIPE. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:50 AM, THE STORM WATER DEPT. DETERMINED THE FUEL DISCHARGE TO THE STORM SEWER WAS DRAINING SOUTH DOWN HOAGLAND BLVD. TO A DITCH WHICH ULTIMATELY DRAINS INTO SHINGLE CREEK. AT APPROXIMATELY 12:10, FLORIDA DEPT. OF TRANSPORTATION AND ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WERE NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND. THE DISCHARGE WAS REPORTED TO NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AND FDEP BUREAU OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE (FDEP-BER). THE STORM WATER DEPARTMENT DAMMED OFF THE DITCH WEST OF HOAGLAND TO STOP THE FLOW OF FUEL FROM CONTAMINATING SHINGLE CREEK AT APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET APART, IN CASE THE FIRST DAM DID NOT HOLD. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (IMS RECOVERY) AND JOHNSONS WRECKER ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 12:23 TO RECOVER FUEL FROM THE OVERTURNED TRANSPORT TRUCK. THE FD BLANKETS THE TRUCK AND SURROUNDING AREA PRIOR TO NORTHSTAR DRILLING THE TANKS TO RECOVER THE REMAINING FUEL. IN ADDITION, THE FD PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AND BOOMS AROUND THE TRAILER TO ABSORB ANY FUEL ON THE ROAD SURFACE. UPON DEPLOYMENT OF THE ABSORBENTS AND FOAM, THE FD ALLOWED PORT CONSOLIDATED TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TRANSPORT TRAILER. THE RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE PORT CONSOLIDATED FACILITY LOCATED IN TAMPA, FLORIDA AND RETURNED TO INVENTORY. THE STORM WATER DEPT. CONFIRMS THAT THE DAMS INSTALLED BY 12:40. IN ADDITION TO THE DAMS, HARD AND SOFT BOOM WERE DEPLOYED BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRA

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL WASTE MINIMIZATION, INC. ("EWMI") PICKED UP A DRUM ON AUGUST 5, 2013 FROM MARCAL MANUFACTURING, LLC ("MARCAL") ON MANIFEST NO. 011811760JJK THAT WAS ULTIMATELY DESTINED FOR THE SAFETY KLEEN SYSTEMS, INC. FACILITY IN SMITHFIELD,KY. THE DRUM WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DELIVERED BY EWMI ON THE SAME DAY TO A 10 DAY TRANSFER FACILITY, OWNED BY HORWITH TRUCKS, INC, LOCATED IN NORTHAMPTON, PA, WHERE IT WAS PLACED INTRANSIT STORAGE UNTIL THE DRUM COULD BE SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY TO SAFETY KLEEN'S LINDEN, NEW JERSEY FACILITY WHERE IT WAS INTENDED TO BE TRANSFERRED TO THEIR SMITHFIELD, KY PLANT.    ON AUGUST 9, 2013, THE MARCAL DRUM WAS PLACED ON A EWMI TRAILER, ALONG WITH SEVERAL CONTAINERS FROM OTHER GENERATORS THAT WERE DESTINED FOR DELIVERY AT SAFETY KLEEN'S FACILITY IN LINDEN, NJ. UNFORTUNATELY, WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS PICKED UP AT THE HORWITH LOCATION, THE MANIFEST THAT REPRESENTED THE MARCAL CONTAINER WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT BEHIND AND DID NOT ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.    THE MARCAL CONTAINER WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DELIVERED ON AUGUST 12,2013 TO THE SAFETY KLEEN LINDEN FACILITY. SEVERAL DAYS AFTER THE AUGUST 12, 2013 SHIPMENT, EWMI DISCOVERED THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT AND DELIVERED IT TO THE SAFETY KLEEN'S LINDEN PLANT. THE MANIFEST WAS IN TURN FORWARDED BY LINDEN FACILITY TO SAFETY KLEEN'S SMITHFIELD FACILITY WHERE THE DRUM WAS ULTIMATELY DELIVERED.
column169: EWMI HAS EXPENDED A GREAT DEAL OF EFFORT TO ENSURE PROPER MANAGEMENT OF THE CONTAINERS OF HAZARDOUS AND NONHAZARDOUS WASTES IT REGULARLY TRANSPORTS. AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, EWMI HAS TAKEN THE FOLLOWING MEASURES TO ADDRESS THIS SITUATION AND TO PREVENT ITS POTENTIAL REOCCURRENCE. SOME OF NEWLY ESTABLISHED OR UPDATED PROCEDURES INCLUDE:  CREATION OF NEW MANIFEST VERIFICATION AND CONTAINER PROCEDURES:  SINCE THE INCIDENT, REFRESHER MANIFEST AND DOT TRAINING HAS BEEN PROVIDED TO THEIR EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN HAZMAT TRANSPORTATION;  ALL EMPLOYEES IN THE MANAGEMENT AND SHIPMENT OF THIS DRUM WERE DISCIPLINED;  EWMI HAS IMPLEMENT AND IMPROVED SEGREGATION SYSTEM FOR MANIFESTS FOR EACH OF THE DIFFERENT DESTINATION FACILITY UTILIZED AT THE 10-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY LOCATION;  THE USE OF AN OUT-BOUND LOAD SHEET IS NOW REQUIRED TO BE USED TO VERIFY ALL OUT-BOUND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS BY EWMI PERSONNEL; AND  A TRANSPORTER LOAD SUMMARY SHEET WILL ALSO BE USED BY ALL PERSONNEL PICKING UP WASTER FROM A CUSTOMER'S LOCATION.

column168: On call Safety Manager received a call Sunday at 16:06 EST by Trucks Inc., a secondary (highway subservice) carrier.   Drivers reported he had a liquid leaking from his trailer, at the time of call material leaking was unknown. Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted and dispatched a response team for clean-up.  4 gallons of Step Down Liquefier from four 5 gallon buckets due to buckets being tipped over.  No storm drains or waterways were impacted by release.  Absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor.  The damaged containers were placed into overpack drums.  All contaminated material was containerized and staged on trailer.  FL DEP Tracking 2013-5411.

Dockworker used incorrect equipment to move a plastic 55 gallon drum. At 2043 EST, Con-way Safety Department contacted ERTS in regards to a UN2491 Ethanolamine release at 2800 Forrest Park Rd. Southeast in Atlanta, GA. It was reported that a 55 gallon drum of the material was punctured releasing all 55 gallons to the interior of the trailer and the concrete below the trailer. ERTS spoke with terminal and he reported that he applied oil dry to attempt to keep the material from entering any drains, he stated that he did not believe any had entered a nearby drain. At 2053 EST, ERTS contacted GA DNR and tracking number 71825 was issued to this release. ERTS coordinated a response with a network contractor and an ETA will be provided as soon as it becomes available. The contractor confirmed that there is some free standing liquids in the bottom of the catch basin and it does appear that some of the material may have entered. At 0006 EST, ERTS contacted Officer Brent with the NRC and tracking number 1056542 was issued to this release. The contractor reported that an estimated 10 gallons had been released from the punctured drum impacting the interior of the trailer and an estimated 12' x 4' area of asphalt/ concrete. The contractor applied a neutralizer and worked in absorbents thoroughly and then containerized them. The contractor collected all free standing liquids from the catch basin. All waste was staged on site for Con-way to manage post incident.
column169: Follow-up with responsible employee per HR policy.

column168: DOCKWORKER USED INCORRECT EQUIPMENT TO MOVE A PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM.    AT 2043 EST, CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED ERTS IN REGARDS TO A UN2491 ETHANOLAMINE RELEASE AT 2800 FORREST PARK RD. SOUTHEAST IN ATLANTA, GA. IT WAS REPORTED THAT A 55 GALLON DRUM OF THE MATERIAL WAS PUNCTURED RELEASING ALL 55 GALLONS TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND THE CONCRETE BELOW THE TRAILER.  ERTS SPOKE WITH TERMINAL AND HE REPORTED THAT HE APPLIED OIL DRY TO ATTEMPT TO KEEP THE MATERIAL FROM ENTERING ANY DRAINS, HE STATED THAT HE DID NOT BELIEVE AND HAD ENTERED A NEARBY DRAIN. AT 2053 EST, ERTS CONTACTED GA DNR AND TRACKING NUMBER 71825 WAS ISSUED TO THIS RELEASE. ERTS COORDINATED A RESPONSE WITH A NETWORK CONTRACTOR AND AN ETA WILL BE PROVIDED AS SOON AS IT BECOMES AVAILABLE.    THE CONTRACTOR CONFIRMED THAT THERE IS SOME FREE STANDING LIQUIDS IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CATCH BASIN AND IT DOES APPEAR THAT SOME OF THE MATERIAL MAY HAVE ENTERED. AT 0006 EST, ERTS CONTACTED OFFICER BRENT WITH THE NRC AND TRACKING NUMBER 1056542 WAS ISSUED TO THIS RELEASE. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT AN ESTIMATED 10 GALLONS HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE PUNCTURED DRUM IMPACTING THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER AND AN ESTIMATED 12'X 4' AREA OF ASPHALT/CONCRETE. THE CONTRACTOR APPLIED A NEUTRALIZER AND WORKED IN ABSORBENTS THOROUGHLY AND THEN CONTAINERIZED THEM. THE CONTRACTOR COLLECTED ALL FREE STANDING LQUIDS FROM THE CATCH BASIN. ALL WASTE WAS STAGED ON SITE FOR CON-WAY TO MANAGE POST INCIDENT.

JASON CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISON TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I ALTERED PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. NEXT I USED PH TAPE TO TEST THE LIQUID.  IT TESTED TO A PH OF 1 FIRST I STARTED CLEANUP ON THE MAIN WALKWAY. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE TO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID TO A PH BETWEEN 6-9 THEN I SOLIDIFIED ANY REMAINING LIQUID & REPEATED THE PROCEDURE OF NEUTRALIZATION/SOLIDIFYING THE LIQUID. LAST, I USED THE SAME PROCEDURE TO CLEAN THE IRREG CHUTE & THE FLOOR NEXT TO THE CHUTE. THEN I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO DMP FOR PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, IFOUND THAT THE GLASS BOTTLE INSIDE HAD SHATTERED.

column168: THE B&M DRIVER PARKED AT THE REST AREA AND INSPECTED HIS TRAILER. DURING THE INSPECTION HE NOTICIED AN ODOR AND LEAKING LIQUID OUT OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER CLLED HIS DISPATCHER TO NOTIFY THEM. WHILE ON THE PHONE OTHER DRIVERS REPORTED THE RELEASE TO THE TRAVEK PLAZA WHICH RESULTED IN THE LOCAL AND STATE POLICE BEING NOTIFIED. THE LOCAL POLICE, LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE POLICE WERE ALL NOTIFIED ABOUT THE RELEASE. B&M CONTACTED ENVIRONEMENTAL MANAGEMENT TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED SWS ENVIRONMENTAL (SWS) TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP. SWS PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER ON SUPPLIED AIR. THE CREW STATED THE NINE (9) TOTES HAD SLID FORWARD TOWARD THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  IT WAS UNCLEAR WHICH TOTE WAS ACTUALLY LEAKING DUE TO THE FACT THAT ALL NINE TOTES WERE CRUSHED INTO EACH OTHER. A DECISION WAS MADE TO DIAPER THE TRAILER AND ESCORT IT TO AES DISPOSAL FACILITY IN CALVERT CITY, KENTUCKY FOR STAGING. THIS WOULD REDUCE THE LEVEL OF CONCERN FOR ALL MOTORIST AT THE TRAVEL PLAZA PLUS PROVIDE MORE ROOM FOR THE SWS TO ACCESS AND WORK ON THE TRAILER.  THE CREW DIAPERED THE TRAILER AND ESCORTED IT. AES WHERE IT WAS PLACED ON POLY SHEETING WITH A BERM TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT WAS LEFT AT THE AES FACILITY FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE NIGHT. ON FRIDAY, AUGUST 30TH THE SWS CREW BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE TOTES FROM THE TRAILER. THE TWO (2) TOTES NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, NUMBERS 8 AND 9 WERE DAMAGE. THE TOTES WERE PLACED IN TO A ROLL OFF CONTAINER. TOTE NUMBER 9 HAD A BOTTOM VALVE THAT HAD BEEN DAMAGED BEYOND REPAIR.TOTE NUMBER 8 HAS STRUCTURAL DAMAGE AND PINHOLES IN THE TOTE BODY. TOTES 7,6,4 AND 3 WERE DAMAGED BUT NOT LEAKING. THE FIVE TOTES WERE TRANSFEREED INTO NEW TOTES FOR SAFETY REASONS. TOTE NUMBER 2 AND 1 WERE UNDAMAGEED AND IN PERFECT CONDITION. THE CREW STATED THE LOAD HAD GONE THROUGH A LOAD SHIFT WHICH HAD CAUSED THE TOTES TO SLIDE FORWARD.

column168: ON THE AFTERNOON OF AUGUST 15, 2013, BRIAN LEMON, V.P. OF OPERATIONS FOR ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS NOTICED THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING FROM ONE OF OUR LOADED TRAILERS. AN ABSORBENT BOOM WAS PLACED AT THE REAR DOOR TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL FREE PRODUCT AND THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO OUR WAREHOUSE DOCK TO FACILITATE UNLOADING AND TO FIND OF THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. PRIOR TO THE OPENING OF THE TRAILER DOOR, MANIFESTS FOR THE LOAD WERE REVIEWED TO DETERMINE WHAT TYPES OF WASTE WERE ON THE TRAILER. AFTER REVIEWING THE MANIFESTS, IT WAS DEEMED SAFE TO ENTER THE TRAILER AND BEGIN UNLOADING. DURING UNLOADING, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS THE FAILURE OF A BOTTOM VALVE ON A TOTE OF CHROMIUM LIQUID, FROM APEX TOOL, LLC. THE VALVE WAS NOT ABLE TO BE FIXED SO THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL WAS PUMPED INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS BY ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS PERSONNEL. WHILE THE IN-TRAILER LEAK WAS BEING REMEDIATED, ADDITIONAL PERSONNEL BEGAN THE CLEAN-UP IN THE PARKING LOT AT THE POINT OF THE INITIAL RELEASE. THE AFFECTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND PLACED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THE AREA WAS FILLED WITH CLEAN FILL AND GRAVEL REPLACED. WITH THE CONSENT OF APEX TOOL, THE MANIFEST WAS CHANGED TO INCLUDE THE 4 DRUMS OF SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL, 2 DRUMS OF WASTE PUMPED FROM THE TOTE AND THE NUMBER OF TOTES WAS REDUCED BY ONE.
column169: ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS, INC.'S DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED TO CHECK ALL CLOSURES ON PACKAGING BEFORE LOADING ON TRANSPORT VEHICLES. ANY CONTAINERS SHOWING EVIDENCE OF FAILURE ARE DENIED FOR PICK-UP. THE GENERATOR HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT THE MANUFACTURER FOR HELP IN POSSIBLY DETERMINING THE CAUSE OF THE VALVE FAILURE CAUSING THIS INCIDENT.

Driver was traveling north on US 87 where the road bends to the left as you travel north. A black pickup southbound failed to stay in his lane and entered our drivers lane causing him to take the truck off the highway. As the pup trailer was attempting to come back onto the roadway it tripped in the soft dirt and rolled over several times. The trailer was mortally damaged and 2940 gallons were released. The sandy soil soaked up all the residual fuel that spilled before we could get any kind of vacuum truck to recover any of it. The duration of the spill was approximately 3 hours from accident to clearing of all equipment.   Remediation was managed by LMH Environmental with current test results negative for ground water contamination. Contaminated soil was removed and remediation completed 2 weeks from the date of the accident.
column169: Truck drivers are being trained in quarterly safety meetings to use defensive driving techniques to keep from leaving the roadway when encountering obstacles in their lane. Response time and duties have been discussed to shorten duration of time from accident till company response vehicles are dispatched to the scene. This is subject to distance from terminal to crash site and measures already in place by responding EMS
