column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM THE RAIL CAR INTO THE STORAGE TANK AT THE HAWKINS, INC. FACILITY, AN OVERFLOW OCCURRED. APPROXIMATELY 750 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED TO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT STRUCTURE SURROUNDING THE TANK, AND ADJACENT SOILS. CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RECOVERED THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA, AND EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOILS. THREE (3)55-GALLON DRUMS OF FREE LIQUID, AND THREE (3) ROLLOFF BOXES OF CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE RECOVERED DURING RESPONSE EFFORTS. SITE WAS MONITORED TO CONFIRM ALL RESIDUALS HAD BEEN REMOVED, AND RESTORED TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: HAWKINS, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: AFTER A PACKAGE FELL OFF THE LOADING DOCK IRREG SLIDE, JASON SUPERVISOR NOTICED A PUDDLE & AN ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  HE NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS OF THE SPILL WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA I COULD SEE THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  U UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSES THE SITUATION.  I SURRONDED THE PUDDLE WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT TO KEEP IT FROM SPREADING FUTHER.  I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY PUT DOWN MORE ABSORBANT TO FULLY SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID.  I SWEPT UP ALL CANTAMINATED ABSORBANT & PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY THEN TOOK THE LEAKING PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, FOUND THAT 1 OF THE GLASS BOTTLES HAD BROKEN.  WHILE I WAS PROCESSING THE PACKAGE, MY SUPERVISOR WENT BACK TO THE AREA BECAUSE THERE WERE STILL COMPLAINTS OF THE ODOR & PUT DOWN BOTH ACTIVATED CARBON & CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT, THEN RESWEPT UP THE AREA.  HE BROUGHT ME THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS FOR ME TO PROCESS.

THE FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO THE CONCRETE SURFACE AT THE CONSIGNEE FACILITY, AND DID NOT IMPACT SURFACE SOILS OR THREATEN TO AFFECT WATERS OF THE STATE.  DARLING INTERNATIONAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP, AND NO OUTSIDE ASSISTANCE WAS REQUIRED.  THERE WERE NO INURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  SITE HAS BEEN DEEMED FOR CLOSURE.
column169: HAWKINS, INC. DBA VERTEX WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: DRIVER WAS LEAVING A WELL SITE AND, UPON ENTERING THE HIGHWAY, FAILED TO NEGOTIATE THE RIGHT TURN CAUSING THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN. THE DRIVER CONTACTED COMPANY MANAGEMENT AND EMERGENCY SERVICES IMMEDIATELY. UPON HITTING THE GROUND THE TRAILER RECEIVED A RUPTURE ON THE PASSENGER SIDE BELOW THE RIGHT, FRONT CORNER OF THE CROWS NEXT. THE RUPTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 INCHES WIDE. PRODUCT BEGAN RELEASING IMMEDIATELY AND CONTINUED TO RELEASE FOR ABOUT 1.5 HRS. IN AN EFFORT TO SLOW THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASE, A BERN OF SAND WAS BUILT ALONG THE PERIMETER OF THE TRAILER. DURING THAT TIME, WE WERE ABLE TO PUMP THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO ONE OF OUR OTHER TRAILERS. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS REMOVED THROUGH THE USE OF A VACUUM TRUCK SERVICE. SAND WAS THROWN ONTO THE SPILLED DIESEL FROM THE TRACTOR'S FUEL TANK UNTIL WE PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE LEAK TO CATCH THE PRODUCT. BIOREMEDIATION TECHNIQUES INCLUDING THE USE OF A BASE LAYER OF SAND, FERTILIZER, OIL BUG, HAY, AND WATER WERE USED TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THE RELEASE ON THE ENVIRONMENT. GRASS SEED WAS ALSO PLANTED.
column169: THROUGH OUR INVESTIGTION, WE GROUND SEVERAL FACTORS THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THE ACCIDENT AND SPILL. THE RAILROAD CROSSING THROUGH THE PRIVATE ROAD TO THE WELL DOESN’T ALLOW ADEQUATE DISTANCE FOR A TRACTOR TRAILER TO CROSS, STOP, AND ENTER THE HIGHWAY SAFELY. THERE ARE ALSO NO ACTIVE SIGNALS TO ALERT THE DRIVER OF AN ONCOMING TRAIN. THE PRIVATE ROAD IS ALSO NARROW WHICH DOESN’T ALLOW A MARGIN OF ERROR WHEN NAVIGATING THE TURN ONTO THE HIGHWAY WHILE TRYING TO AVOID TRAFFIC. WE FOUND THAT THE LOCATION HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY REPORTED FOR THESE ISSUES. DUE TO THESE ISSUES, THE DRIVER WAS NOT CITED BY THE POLICE OFFICIAL. SINCE THERE WAS AN ONCOMING TRAIN AND THE DRIVER ACTED IN A MANNER TO AVOID A MORE SERIOUS INCIDENT, WE ADMINISTERED MINOR REPRIMAND TO THE DRIVER. THE STATE POLICE OFFICER STATED HE WOULD SUBMIT ANOTHER REQUEST TO IMPROVE THE LOCATION IN EFFORT TO MAKE IT SAFER FOR TRUCKS TO ENTER OR EXIT.

ON AUGUST 20,2013, AT APPROXIMATELY 14:00, THE DRIVER OF A FUEL TRANSPORT WAS ATTEMPTING TO BACK DOWN A GRAVEL RAMP TO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK UNLOADING AREA. THE TRAILER MISSED THE RAMP AND TILTED DURING THE ATTEMPT, BECOMING TOP HEAVY AND ROLLING OVER. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE NEAREST HOSPITAL BY AN ON-SITE FOREMAN. EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE CONTACTED AND A TEMPORARY BERM WAS CONSTRUCTED ON THE DOWN-SLOPE END OF THE ACCIDENT AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES FOR POTENTIAL FUEL SPILLAGE. APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF DIESEL  FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRANSPORT TRAILER DURING THE ROLLOVER. THE DIESEL REMAINING IN THE TRANSPORT TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED TO A SECONDART TRAILER AND DELIVERED THE CUSTOMERS TANK. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE THEN REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.    ON AUGUST 22 & 23, 2013, APPROXIMATELY 80 CUBIC YARDS OF DIESEL IMPACTED SOIL WERE EXCAVATED AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE. SOIL SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FROM THE BASE AND SIDEWALLS OF THE EXCAVATION AT DEPTHS RANGING FROM ONE TO THREE FEET BELOW THE GROUND SURFACE. LABORATORY DETECTION LIMITS. THESE ANALYTICAL RESULTS ALONG WITH FIELD OBSERVATIONS BELOW LABORATORY DETECTION LIMITS. THESE ANALYTICAL RESULTS ALONG WITH FIELD OBSERVATIONS INDICATE THAT THE SURFACE RELEASE WAS SUCCESSFULLY REMEDIATED.

column168: TIME   EVENT  7:30   UNIT ARRIVES AT CROWN CORK & SEAL BALTIMORE MD PER SCHEDULE         DRIVER PRESENTS CUSTOMER WITH SHIPPING DOCUMENTS         SAMPLE TAKEN, VERIFICATION OF PRODUCT & SEALS    8:10   DRIVER AUTHORIZED TO PROCEED WITH UNLOADING PROCESS: DRIVER REMOVES HOSE FROM CARGO TANK, COUPLES AND SECURES DELIVERY HOSE TO CARGO TANK.         RECEIVER COUPLES DELIVERY HOSE TO DELIVERY PIPE, DRIVER VERIFIES DELIVERY HOSE IS COUPLED AND SECURE.         DRIVER VENTS TANKS & IS AUTHORIZED TO OPEN VALVES.         CROWN PERSONNEL ENTER FACILITY START DELIVERY PUMP TO STORAGE TANK LOCATED WITHIN BUILDING.         DRIVER MAINTAINS VISUAL MONITORING OF CARGO TANK & DELIVERY HOSE.  8:55   CROWN CORK & SEAL RECEIVER EMERGED FROM BUILDING INSTRUCTING DRIVER TO CLOSE VALVES THAT THERE HAD BEEN A SPILL WITHIN THE PLANT.         DRIVER INSTRUCTED NOT TO DISCONNECT DELIVERY HOSE AND TO REMAIN IN ATTENDANCE.         DRIVER NOTIFIED THE READING ON THE RECEIVING TANK WAS MISREAD RESULTING IN A SPILL.  17:30  DRIVER INSTRUCTED TO DISCONNECT RECEIVING HOSE AND SECURE CARGO TANK.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WOULD BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  18:10  UNIT DEPARTS CROWN FACILITY BALTIMORE MD    CROWN HAS A STRICT FACILITY ACCESS POLICY WHICH DOES NOT ALLOW DRIVERS TO ENTER THEIR FACILITY.    THE SPILL OCCURRED AND WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE FACILITY OF CROWN CORK BEYOND THE ACCESS OF CONTROL OF WIKELS' DRIVER.  CROWN PERSONNEL ORCHESTRATE THE ENTIRE UNLOADING PROCESS WHICH INCLUDED, GAUGING TANK LEVEL, OPERATE PUMP, AND MONITOR THE PROCESS WITHIN THE FACILITY.    THEREFORE ON THE ABOVE FACTS THE CARRIER'S RESPONSIBILITY ENDS AT THE POINT OF THE DELIVERY HOSE IS COUPLED TO THE RECEIVING PIPE AND HENCE THE CONSIGNEE TAKES POSSESSION OF THE PRODUCT AT SAID POINT.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: The Miller driver was in route and stopped at 17:40 to check his truck on the side of highway 287 north just outside of Waxahachie, TX. While performing his load check the driver found product, nitric acid, leaking from the trailer, a1984 Fruehauf MC-312 stainless steel tank trailer, at the bottom of the tank just forward of the top dome area. The material was coming from a weep hole in one of the ring stifferners. He immediately retrieved his on-board emergency response supplies and placed a 3 gallon plastic bucket under the leaking material to contain it. He notified local authorities and requested assistance from the local fire department. He also notified the company. The Waxahachie fire department responded and assisted the driver to contain the leaking material by providing more buckets to capture the leaking material. TAS Environmental from the FT Worth/Dallas area was dispatched to the scene to take over the containment of the leaking nitric, and to facilitate the transfer of the material. We could not locate a compatible trailer for nitric in the Dallas area so a nitric trailer and company response team were dispatched from El Dorado, AR and a Safety Supervisor was dispatched from Houston, TX. The product transfer was completed the next morning at 05:15.

column168: IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT THE BACK TRAILER HAD APPROX 5,000 GALLONS OF PROPANE IN IT. A SECOND TRANSPORT DRIVEN BY KIM WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT AND AS MUCH LIQUID PUMPED OUT OF THE TIPPED OVER TRAILER AS WE COULD GET. CHP WOULD ALLOW US THE TIME TO PUMP THE REMAINING PROPANE OUT OF THE TRAILER ONCE IT WAS TURNED BACK UPRIGHT. THE TOW COMPANY HAD TO TOW THE TRAILER WITH THE REMAINING PROPANE IN IT.    OFFICER OKAZAKI WAS THE CHP OFFICER THAT WANTED THE ROAD REOPEND AND MADE THE DECISION NOT TO ALLOW US TO PUMP THE REMAINING PROPANE OUT OF THE TRAILER.    WE ASKED THE OFFICER AND TOW TRUCK COMPANY SUPERVISOR IF THEIR TOW DRIVER AND TOW TRUCK SUPERVISOR CONVERSED WITH THE DRIVER AND CAME BACK TO US AND SAID HE WAS CLEARED TO TRANSPORT THE TRAILER.    I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE JUST AFTER 1:00 PM. THE TWO VEHICLES OUR DRIVER STRUCK HAD ALREADY BEEN TOWED AND DRIVEN AWAY FROM THE SCENE. IT TOOK APROX. 4 HOURS TO GET THE TRAILER PUMPED OFF AND MOVED BACK TO THE UPRIGHT POSITIONS. ED TAMAGRI DROVE THE TRUCK AND FRONT TRAILER OF BILLY'S TRUCK BACK TO THE MODESTO YARD. ED WESTLUND AND ROBERT WESTLUND AND ROBERT MCCOWN WERE ON SITE TO ASSIST WITH PUMPING THE PROPANE OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE TRANSPORT. SANDI TENBRINK WAS ON SITE AS WELL AND TRANSPORTED BILLY TO THE MEDICAL FACILITY FOR HIS DRUG SCREEN AND ALCOHOL TEST, SHE THEN DROVE HIM BACK TO THE OFFICE TO HIS PERSONAL VEHICLE.
column169: THE EMPLOYEE WAS TERMINATED AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT. THIS INCIDENT WAS ALSO DISCUSSED WITH ALL COMPANY DRIVERS DURING THE MONTHLY SAFETY MEETING AND RE-TRAINING WAS GIVEN IN REGARDS TO DISTRACTED DRIVING.    SINCE THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF HAZRDOUS MATERIALS  AND ALL SAFETY SYSTEMS ON THE TRAILER PERFORMED AND FUNCTIONED CORRECTLY. NO ACTIONS WERE TAKEN IN REGARDS TO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE.
